{"id":"1903.08056","submitter":"Balazs Patkos","authors":"Bal\\'azs Patk\\'os","title":"On the general position problem on Kneser graphs","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In a graph $G$, a geodesic between two vertices $x$ and $y$ is a shortest\npath connecting $x$ to $y$. A subset $S$ of the vertices of $G$ is in general\nposition if no vertex of $S$ lies on any geodesic between two other vertices of\n$S$. The size of a largest set of vertices in general position is the general\nposition number that we denote by $gp(G)$. Recently, Ghorbani et al, proved\nthat for any $k$ if $n\\ge k^3-k^2+2k-2$, then $gp(Kn_{n,k})=\\binom{n-1}{k-1}$,\nwhere $Kn_{n,k}$ denotes the Kneser graph. We improve on their result and show\nthat the same conclusion holds for $n\\ge 2.5k-0.5$ and this bound is best\npossible. Our main tools are a result on cross-intersecting families and a\nslight generalization of Bollob\\'as's inequality on intersecting set pair\nsystems.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 19 Mar 2019 15:35:54 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sun, 21 Jul 2019 10:34:15 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-07-23"}
